Absolutely! Implementing **reactive signals** for **fine-grained state management** in a C++ GUI framework is relatively advanced, but modern C++ can be quite expressive, and this style is gaining traction due to frameworks like [Signals](https://github.com/AndreyG/cpp-signal), as well as inspiration from JavaScript frameworks (React, Solid.js, etc.).

Here’s a **conceptual overview**, and then a **sample implementation** that you could adapt.

---

## Concept

**Reactive signals** means variables that, when updated, notify dependents so only specific UI parts re-render. This avoids broad, inefficient redraws and enables composable, predictable state/updates.

Core building blocks:
- **Signal**: A wrapper for mutable state, able to notify subscribers when its value changes.
- **Slots/Subscribers/Effects**: Functions/UI elements that react to changes.
- **Wiring**: UI components connect their visibility/state to relevant signals.
- **Fine-Grained**: Updates only propagate to affected subscribers, enabling high performance.

---

## Basic Signal Implementation in C++

Here's a minimal setup:

```cpp
#include <functional>
#include <vector>
#include <iostream>

template<typename T>
class Signal {
public:
    using Callback = std::function<void(const T&)>;
    Signal(const T& value) : value_(value) {}

    // Subscribe to value changes
    void subscribe(Callback cb) {
        subscribers_.emplace_back(std::move(cb));
        cb(value_); // notify initial value if desired
    }

    // Set new value and notify subscribers if changed
    void set(const T& new_value) {
        if (value_ != new_value) {
            value_ = new_value;
            for (auto& sub : subscribers_)
                sub(value_);
        }
    }

    // Read current value
    const T& get() const { return value_; }
private:
    T value_;
    std::vector<Callback> subscribers_;
};
```

### Example Usage

Suppose you have some UI elements:

```cpp
Signal<int> counter{0};

void render() {
    std::cout << "Rendering counter: " << counter.get() << std::endl;
}

int main() {
    // Subscribe render function to counter changes
    counter.subscribe([](const int& val) {
        render();
    });

    // Simulate UI: user increments counter
    counter.set(1); // Will trigger render
    counter.set(2); // Will trigger render again
}
```

**Each time you call `set` on `counter`, only dependent UI parts re-render.**

---

## Integrating With a GUI (e.g., ImGui, Qt)

You would connect each UI widget’s state (value, enabled, etc.) to a Signal. When a signal changes, only that widget (or function) updates, not the whole UI tree.

**(Example for reactive label in pseudo-ImGui)**

```cpp
Signal<std::string> label_text{"Hello"};

void render_label() {
    // Called every on label_text change
    ImGui::Text("%s", label_text.get().c_str());
    // Or with Qt: label->setText(QString::fromStdString(label_text.get()));
}

void setup() {
    label_text.subscribe([](const std::string&) { render_label(); });
}

void on_button_press() {
    label_text.set("World!"); // Only label will update
}
```

---

## Advanced: Dependency Tracking (Automatic)

You can make a more sophisticated version that tracks which computations depend on which signals, similar to Solid.js. This requires a global context to register dependencies while functions run. This is more advanced, but let me know if you want to see it!

---

## Libraries and Further Reading

- [cpp-signal](https://github.com/AndreyG/cpp-signal) – minimal implementation
- [reactive-cpp](https://github.com/jwbargsten/reactive-cpp) – more advanced
- [implot/discussions/104](https://github.com/epezent/implot/discussions/104)
- Concepts: [Understanding “Signals” in GUIs (Qt)](https://doc.qt.io/qt-6/signalsandslots.html)

---

## Summary

- **Signal** objects hold state and notify subscribers on change.
- UI functions/widgets subscribe to signals affecting their state.
- Only widgets affected by the changed signal update (“fine-grained”).
- Can be extended for automatic dependency tracking or batching, etc.

If you want a **ready-to-use header**, a demo with ImGui or Qt, or a more advanced example with automatic tracking, just ask!

SolidJS's signals form the core of its fine-grained reactivity system. Understanding how SolidJS tracks dependencies and updates computations (effects, memos, etc.) involves a look under the hood at how its **reactive graph** is built and traversed.

Below is a high-level, step-by-step explanation and a simplified example of the **internals** for SolidJS signals, dependency tracking, and effect propagation.

---

## 1. **Signals as Reactive Primitives**

A **signal** in SolidJS is a wrapper around a value that maintains a list of observers—functions that should run if the value changes. When you read a signal, it registers the current computation as a dependent.

```javascript
function createSignal(value) {
  let observers = new Set();

  function read() {
    if (currentComputation) {
      observers.add(currentComputation);
      currentComputation.dependencies.add(observers);
    }
    return value;
  }

  function write(newValue) {
    if (value !== newValue) {
      value = newValue;
      // Notify all observers (computations that depend on this signal)
      for (const obs of observers) obs.run();
    }
  }

  return [read, write];
}
```

---

## 2. **Dependency Tracking (Reactive Graph Creation)**

When a computation (like an effect or memo) runs, Solid sets a global variable `currentComputation` to the currently executing computation. As you read signals inside the computation, each signal records the current computation in its observer list.

This creates an internal **reactive graph** where:
- **Nodes** = computations/effects/memos
- **Edges** = "depends on" relationships from computations to signals

**Setting up the computation:**

```javascript
let currentComputation = null;

class Computation {
  constructor(fn) {
    this.fn = fn;
    this.dependencies = new Set();
    this.run();
  }

  run() {
    // Cleanup previous dependencies
    this.dependencies.forEach(depSet => depSet.delete(this));
    this.dependencies.clear();
    // Set current executing computation
    const prev = currentComputation;
    currentComputation = this;
    try {
      this.fn();
    } finally {
      currentComputation = prev;
    }
  }
}
```

---

## 3. **Creating an Effect (Computation/Observer)**

An **effect** (or a memoized computation) is a chunk of code that should rerun whenever any of the signals it uses are updated. Internally, this is what happens:

```javascript
function createEffect(fn) {
  new Computation(fn);
}
```

When an effect runs:
- It reads signals.
- Each signal records the effect as an observer.
- If the signal is written to later, it notifies its observers, re-running the effects.

---

## 4. **Propagation & Update**

When `set(signal, value)` is called, it:
- Updates the value.
- Walks the set of current observers (computations that depend on this signal).
- Calls their `.run()` method to re-execute them.
- This may read new signals (restructuring dependencies if needed).

This propagation is extremely fine-grained: only effects truly reliant on a signal's value are re-run.

---

## 5. **Resource Cleanup**

Each computation must clean up its dependencies after every run. If a computation no longer reads from a particular signal, it's removed from the signal's observers. This is why we call `depSet.delete(this)` in `Computation.run()` before re-running the function.

---

## 6. **Summary Diagram**

```
signalA <-- computation1 (effect)
signalB <-- computation1 (effect)
signalA <-- computation2 (memo)

set(signalA, ...) triggers computation1 & computation2
```

---

## 7. **References and Further Reading**

- [SolidJS Reactive Primitives Docs](https://www.solidjs.com/docs/latest/api#creatingsignal)
- [SolidJS Internals (reactivity package on GitHub)](https://github.com/solidjs/solid/blob/main/packages/solid/src/reactive/signal.js)
- [Article: Solid’s Reactivity: How do signals work?](https://dev.to/modderme123/solids-reactivity-how-do-signals-work-58g2)
- [Blog: Building Reactivity from Scratch (simplified models)](https://ryansolid.com/blog/building-reactivity-from-scratch)

---

**TL;DR:**  
**SolidJS signals keep track of which computations are using them by registering the current computation as an observer when read. When a signal updates, it notifies only the computations that depend on it, thus implementing an efficient reactive graph for dependency tracking and update propagation.**

